<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="648" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[150,759,654,1157]" pageId="9" pageNumber="648">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[150,261,686,709]" pageId="9" pageNumber="648">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species was described based on 
<specimenCount box="[652,759,686,709]" pageId="9" pageNumber="648" type="male">two males</specimenCount>
from Pozuzo near Oxapampa (
<collectingRegion box="[462,525,718,741]" country="Peru" name="Pasco" pageId="9" pageNumber="648">Pasco</collectingRegion>
Dept., 
<collectingCountry box="[598,648,718,741]" name="Peru" pageId="9" pageNumber="648">Peru</collectingCountry>
) deposited in MNHN. Maxim Smirnov (
<collectingCountry box="[475,549,750,773]" name="Russia" pageId="9" pageNumber="648">Russia</collectingCountry>
) has a single male collected at Satipo (
<collectingRegion box="[370,429,782,805]" country="Peru" name="Junin" pageId="9" pageNumber="648">Junín</collectingRegion>
Dept., 
<collectingCountry box="[514,565,782,805]" name="Peru" pageId="9" pageNumber="648">Peru</collectingCountry>
) (
<figureCitation box="[589,671,782,805]" captionStart="Figs 38–42. 38" captionStartId="7.[150,187,1307,1326]" captionTargetBox="[160,1425,193,1293]" captionTargetId="figure-347@7.[160,1425,189,1293]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Figs 38–42. 38 – Cupecuara santossilvai Audureau, 2014, male, dorsal view. 39–42 – C. soledari (Martins &amp; Galileo, 2001), holotype female:39 – dorsal view; 40 – ventral view; 41 – lateral view; 42 – frontal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5177916" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5177916/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="648">Fig. 38</figureCitation>
), which constitutes a new department record. Examination of a photograph of the 
<typeStatus box="[350,446,846,869]" pageId="9" pageNumber="648">holotype</typeStatus>
, photograph of the specimen from the Smirnov collection, as well as photographs of two additional specimens (both females and not available for publication), shows that the black areas on elytra are somewhat variable: anterior macula reaching from middle to posterior third; posterior macula occupying the entire distal area or not reaching the sides; anterior margin of the posterior macula somewhat transverse or slightly projected forward along suture. Unfortunately, we have no specimens at our disposal to study.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
